The most striking development was the open use of federal criminal power against named political adversaries. In Virginia, Lindsey Halligan, a newly installed U.S. attorney and former personal lawyer to Donald Trump, secured indictments of New York Attorney General Letitia James on bank fraud and false-statement charges tied to a Virginia mortgage. Career prosecutors had already concluded there was no probable cause, and one resigned rather than sign the case. A top line prosecutor, Elizabeth Yusi, told colleagues she would decline charges, only to see Halligan take the file to a grand jury herself. At the same time, Halligan delivered an indictment of former FBI director James Comey for allegedly lying to Congress in 2020. Comey pleaded not guilty and signaled a defense based on vindictive and selective prosecution. These cases did not arise from neutral case selection. They followed months of presidential demands to \'93go after\'94 particular names. Law here is not a limit. It is a weapon in the president\'92s hand.\
