The pattern around those indictments makes the shift in power clearer. Attorney General Pam Bondi appeared before the Senate Judiciary Committee and refused to answer basic questions about her dismantling of the public integrity section, her closure of an investigation into border czar Tom Homan despite an alleged bribery recording, and her handling of the Epstein files. Senators pressed her on why the unit that once approved charges against members of Congress had been stripped of staff and authority. They asked why immigration judges with high asylum grant rates had been fired or transferred in large numbers. Bondi\'92s answers were evasive or absent. Outside the hearing room, 282 former DOJ officials released a letter warning that the department was being turned into an instrument of presidential retribution. The moral floor of ethics and restraint is thin here. The people who know the institution best say it is being hollowed from within.\
