At the same time, the justice system\'92s treatment of allies and potential allies moved in the opposite direction. The investigation into Tom Homan, who had allegedly promised immigration contracts in exchange for $50,000 from an undercover agent, was closed after Trump took office, with Bondi insisting there was \'93no credible evidence\'94 despite the recording. Michael Ben\'92Ary, a senior national security prosecutor, was fired after a pro-Trump commentator attacked him online as an ally of a former deputy attorney general. The FBI dismissed or reassigned agents who had worked on Trump-related cases, including one close to retirement. Nearly half of FBI agents in the largest field offices were shifted to immigration enforcement, and hundreds of DHS national security specialists were told to move into immigration roles or risk their jobs. In this environment, the law\'92s edge falls hardest on those who cross the president, while those near him find investigations closed, oversight furloughed, and staff reshuffled out of the way.\
