If law was one front, force was another. The administration treated National Guard units as a flexible domestic tool, to be moved across state lines and federalized over local objections. Trump authorized the deployment of 300 Illinois National Guard members to protect ICE facilities in Chicago and welcomed 400 Texas Guard troops sent by Governor Greg Abbott to Illinois and Oregon. These moves came after a federal judge in Oregon, Karin Immergut, had already blocked the federalization of the Oregon Guard and warned against blurring civil and military power. When the administration tried to route around that order by sending California Guard troops to Portland, she extended her injunction to cover any state\'92s Guard. In Chicago, Illinois Attorney General Kwame Raoul and Governor JB Pritzker sued to stop the deployments, calling them an unlawful \'93war\'94 on their state. U.S. District Judge April Perry first declined to block the Texas Guard, then, after further argument, issued a two-week halt on both Texas and Illinois Guard deployments, finding no credible evidence of rebellion. A second judge issued a related order. The executive\'92s appetite for military tools is clear. So is the judiciary\'92s willingness, for now, to say no.\
